<stack-static>
    <statement><p><p>
A student stands some distance from a tower and observes the angle of elevation of the top to be <m>{30}</m><m>^\circ</m>. The student then walks <m>{9}</m> m closer to the tower and observes the angle to be <m>{60}</m>°. Find the height of the tower.
</p>

<p>
Give your answer correct to <alert>2 decimal places</alert>.
</p>

<p>
Height = <fillin characters="8" name="ans1"/> m  
</p></p></statement>
    <solution><p><h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>
Let the distance from the second position (the closer point) to the tower be <m>x</m> m.
</p>

<p>
Since the student walked <m>{9}</m> m closer, the distance from the first position to the tower was:
</p>

<p>
<me>
x + {9}
</me>
</p>

<p>
Step 1: Form an equation from the first position.
</p>

<p>
<me>
\tan {30}^\circ = \frac{h}{x + {9}}
</me>
</p>

<p>
So,
</p>

<p>
<me>
h = (x + {9})\tan {30}^\circ
</me>
</p>

<p>
Step 2: Form an equation from the second position.
</p>

<p>
<me>
\tan {60}^\circ = \frac{h}{x}
</me>
</p>

<p>
So,
</p>

<p>
<me>
h = x\tan {60}^\circ
</me>
</p>

<p>
Step 3: Since both expressions are equal to <m>h</m>, equate them:
</p>

<p>
<me>
(x + {9})\tan {30}^\circ = x\tan {60}^\circ
</me>
</p>

<p>
Substitute <m>\tan 30^\circ = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}</m> and <m>\tan 60^\circ = \sqrt{3}</m>:
</p>

<p>
<me>
(x + {9})\cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} = x\sqrt{3}
</me>
</p>

<p>
Multiply both sides by <m>\sqrt{3}</m>:
</p>

<p>
<me>
x + {9} = 3x
</me>
</p>

<p>
<me>
{9} = 2x
</me>
</p>

<p>
<me>
x = \frac{9}{2}
</me>
</p>

<p>
Step 4: Find the height using <m>h = x\tan 60^\circ</m>.
</p>

<p>
<me>
h = \frac{9}{2}\times \sqrt{3}
</me>
</p>

<p>
<me>
h \approx {7.79}\text{ m}
</me>
</p>

<p>
Therefore, the height of the tower is:
</p>

<p>
<me>
\boxed{{7.79} \text{ m}}
</me>
</p></p></solution>
    <answer><p><m>7.79</m></p></answer>
</stack-static>